  		<h4>First-trimester Screening </h4>
  		<p><b>11 week - 13week 5 days</b></p>
  		<p>Screening test means various test to identify those cases have high risk for disease. In 1st trimester there are various blood test along with ultrasound that allow doctors and parents to assess the baby’s health who are at higher risk of structural anomaly or chromosomal abnormality most likely down syndrome. There are routine screenings in the first and second trimester, and additional screenings may be required.</p>
  		<p>The first trimester is very very important, because this is when the baby’s internal organs and body systems are being formed, laying the foundation for its future health. The first-trimester screening is typically offered at 10-13 weeks.</p>
  		<p>This first screening seeks to determine the baby’s gestational age and set the expected due date, analyze how the fetus is developing by checking the placement of its limbs and comparing its size to what is expected for its age, check that the placenta is attached properly, evaluate the amount and quality of the amniotic fluid, check for risks of miscarriage, look for signs of chromosomal anomalies that would be visible on an ultrasound (such as by checking nuchal translucency), and to rule out any severe congenital defects in the internal organs, such as the brain, skeleton, or heart.</p>
  		<p>The most important benefit of the screening ultrasound is to give the future parents and monitoring physician detailed information on the baby’s health and development and determine the risk of birth defects, chromosomal abnormalities, or hereditary diseases.</p>
  		<p>Detecting issues early has a big effect. It gives the chance to start treating the disease as early as possible, and if a complete cure is not possible, at least alleviate the symptoms as much as possible. If the doctor notices any deviations from the norm, the pregnancy is monitored especially closely, which helps prevent any complications or premature labor.</p>
  		<p>Pregnancy screenings are harmless to both mother and child. They are reasonably accurate, but it’s important to understand that they can’t give any guarantees. The accuracy of the screening depends on many factors, chief among them the skill of the doctors and techs and the quality of their equipment.</p>
  		<p>Do you know that parts of your baby’s DNA circulate in your blood? Noninvasive prenatal testing (NIPT) involves a simple blood screening that analyzes that DNA (it’s called cell-free DNA, or cfDNA) to screen baby’s risk for a number of genetic disorders, including Down syndrome.</p>

  		<p><b>What is noninvasive prenatal testing (NIPT)?</b></p>
  		<p>NIPT is a prenatal screening, which looks at DNA from your baby's placenta in a sample of your blood to identify whether you’re at increased risk of giving birth to a child with a genetic disorder. A screening like NIPT cannot, however, determine for sure whether your baby actually has a chromosomal disorder, only the likelihood of having that condition. But even though it can’t tell for sure whether your baby has a genetic abnormality, it is highly accurate — 97 to 99 percent accuracy for three of the most common conditions.</p>
  		<p>The results of an NIPT screening can help you and your doctor decide next steps, including whether to have a diagnostic test like chorionic villus sampling (CVS) or amniocentesis (“amnio”). These genetic tests analyze a baby's own genetic material, collected from the amniotic fluid or placenta, to tell with 100 percent certainty whether a baby has a chromosome abnormality. However, they are invasive, which means they slightly increase risk of abortion. </p>
  		<p><b>How is NIPT done?</b></p>
  		<p>Because an NIPT involves only a quick blood draw with a needle and syringe, it's safe for you and your baby. All you’ll need to do is offer up your arm at the doctor’s office or a lab. Your sample is then sent to a lab, where a technician will look at the cfDNA in your blood for signs of abnormalities.</p>
